    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down | Beckenham, Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Feb. 12/79</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I am sorry to say that I can give you no information.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                    <p>I have forgotten the very little Greek which I once knew. Nor have I ever read, to my shame be it spoken, the works of Aristotle. From extracts, which I have seen, I have an unbounded respect for him, as one of the greatest, if not the greatest observer, that ever lived.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">No letters from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1111.xml">Crawley</ref> have been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD cited the observations of Aristotle in <hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 4th ed., p. xiii, <hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 1: 24, 75 and 277, and 2: 51, and <hi rend="italic">Cross and self fertilisation</hi>, pp. 415–16. CD’s Reading notebook (1838–51) contains the entry ‘read Aristotle to see whether any of my views are ancient’ (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 4, Appendix IV, 119: 2v).</note>
        </div>
    
